  "response_text": "# Realistic Movement Strategies for Desk Work + Fatigue\n\n## Micro-movements (minimal energy, high frequency)\n- **Desk stretches**: neck rolls, shoulder shrugs, wrist circles (2-3 min hourly)\n- **Seated exercises**: marching in place, seated twists, desk push-ups\n- **Standing breaks**: stand for calls, alternate sitting/standing desk positions\n- These add up without requiring motivation\n\n## Low-intensity options that conserve energy\n- **Gentle walks**: 10-minute breaks instead of one long session\n- **Swimming or water aerobics**: buoyancy reduces strain\n- **Tai chi or gentle yoga**: slower pace, builds strength gradually\n- **Stationary cycling**: controlled intensity, no impact\n\n## Realistic scheduling\n- **Aim for consistency over intensity** (15 min most days > sporadic hard workouts)\n- **Morning movement**: easier when energy is highest\n- **Post-lunch walks**: counteracts afternoon slump\n- **Track what actually happens**, not ideals—adjust accordingly\n\n## Energy management tips\n- Pair activity with something pleasant (music, podcast, scenery)\n- Start smaller than feels necessary—momentum often builds\n- Rest days are part of the plan, not failures\n- Monitor if activity helps or drains energy (varies individually)\n\n## When to adjust\nConsider consulting your doctor about whether fatigue might benefit from other interventions (sleep, nutrition, pacing strategies) alongside movement.\n\nWhat type of movement sounds most doable for your situation?",
